</div>
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en">Paul-Louis Landsberg</h1>
									<div id="bodyContent" class="mw-body-content">
									<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p><b>Paul-Louis Landsberg</b> (1901–1944) was a twentieth century <a href="/wiki/Existentialist" title="Existentialist" class="mw-redirect">Existentialist</a> <a href="/wiki/Philosopher" title="Philosopher">philosopher</a> who is known for his arguments in support of <a href="/wiki/Euthanasia" title="Euthanasia">euthanasia</a> as an acceptable method of <a href="/wiki/Suicide" title="Suicide">suicide</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> His arguments are used today by <a href="/wiki/Christian" title="Christian">Christian</a> proponents of euthanasia. His best known works are <i>The Experience of Death</i> and <i>The Moral Problem of Suicide</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Landsberg lectured at the Universities of <a href="/wiki/Bonn" title="Bonn">Bonn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Madrid" title="Madrid">Madrid</a> and <a href="/wiki/Paris" title="Paris">Paris</a>, among others. He was a pupil of <a href="/wiki/Martin_Heidegger" title="Martin Heidegger">Martin Heidegger</a>, <a href="/wiki/Edmund_Husserl" title="Edmund Husserl">Edmund Husserl</a> and <a href="/wiki/Max_Scheler" title="Max Scheler">Max Scheler</a>, continuing their work in <a href="/wiki/Phenomenology_(philosophy)" title="Phenomenology (philosophy)">Phenomenology</a> to tackle several vital subjects, including <a href="/wiki/Personal_identity" title="Personal identity">personal identity</a>, <a href="/wiki/Death" title="Death">death</a> and <a href="/wiki/Suicide" title="Suicide">suicide</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> He was a close friend of the Christian Existentialist <a href="/wiki/Emmanuel_Mounier" title="Emmanuel Mounier">Emmanuel Mounier</a> and a key contributor to the philosophical journal <a href="/wiki/Esprit_(magazine)" title="Esprit (magazine)"><i>Esprit</i></a> (1913-2013).<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Landsberg was hounded by the <a href="/wiki/Gestapo" title="Gestapo">Gestapo</a> for most of his life, both because of his <a href="/wiki/Jewish" title="Jewish" class="mw-redirect">Jewish</a> family background and due to his expression of <a href="/wiki/Anti-Nazi" title="Anti-Nazi" class="mw-redirect">Anti-Nazi</a> sentiments. He was captured by the Gestapo and deported to Oranienburg <a href="/wiki/Concentration_Camp" title="Concentration Camp" class="mw-redirect">Concentration Camp</a> towards the end of the war and died there of physical and mental exhaustion in April 1944.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
